ving\nall the standard styles, as\nthe extremist.\nts, $10 to $45.\nty garments of correct fashions\nvisit the swell shops, in New\ngreater variety of smart styles\nlis than we offer.\ni\nAll Customers\nchases Charged.\nis the rule, not the\nchaser of us is invited\nvhen we will arrange\na little each week or j\nrour convenience.\nHi rrnrrnn n i&ib) mw&\ne> (s\\ y\\yjiuuftiro im.\nCo.,\nEye No W.\n\ni!\nf jp ,V\\\nX l I\n\ni\n*^Dorothy\nDodd'' Shoes is\nFew women realize how\nlit in a shoe saves one'sknow\nthat if each of your\nIs, walking would be imaccumulated\nsaving of\nday from wearing \"Doro)orothv\nDodds\" will interowns\nare extremely tashe\nPatent Leathers fill the\niun Metals are, as always,\nm all, and all at the modces.\nsively in this city.\nI\nPa. Ave. and 9th St.\nTorpedo Explosion by Wireless.\nSpecial IMspateh to The Star.\nL/ONDON, April 10.?The Evening News\ndescribes the torpedo Invented by Grendall\nMathews, which the inventor says can be\ncontrolled absolutely up to a distance of\nmiles and which can 1?3 exploded by\nconcussion or at any moment desired by\n'means of a wireless telegraph system.\nNo connection to guide the instrument\nis necessary between it and the toipedo\nboat from which it is discharged. The inI\nventor also asserts that he has.discovered\nIan electrical wave which cannot be in'terfercd\nwith.\nHOPE UNO CONFIDENCE\n\nEarly Return of Prosperity\nLooked for in Georgia.\nDEPRESSION TEMPORARY\n\nFelt Mostly by Lumber Mills and\nthe Railways.\n_____\nFARMERS ON A CASH BASIS\nHave Been Holding Their Cotton for\nHigh Prices?Some Results\nof Northern Invasion.\nBY WILLIAM E. CI RTIS.\nSpecial CorrP!<poiiiJen<*p of The Star and the\nChiraco Record-Herald.\nAUGUSTA. Ga.. March 30. 190S.\nWihen T asked Mr. Thomas K. Scott, the\ngeneral manager of the Georgia railroad,\nand one of the best informed men in the\nsouth, concerning the effect of the recent\nfinancial depression upon railway earnings\nin that section he replied that it\nwas due to several causes which he believed\nto be only temporary, and lie could\nnot imagine any reason why a revival of\ncommercial activity should not occur\nsoon.\n\"Georgia is principally an agricultural\nstate.\" said Mr. Scott. \"The manufacture\nof metals is confined to Atlanta, and some\nof the plants tiherc, I think, were closed\niur a lime uuriug uic ictcui ocv c?u uv- i\npression. which, of course, affected us as\nit did all the rest of the country, but not\nto so great a degree. My impression is\nthat all of the shops that shut down have\nalready resumed operations. The prin-\ncipal other manufacturing interests of j\nGeorgia are textiles, cotton seed oil. meal,\netc., lumber and car building. I have not\nheard of any cotton factories closing uown\nin this section of tihe country. During the\nrecent prosperous times the managers of\nour textile mills have not been able to secure\nenough operatives to run all of their\nmachinery, and have been behind on their\norders. They were probably running\nabout 80 per cent of their capacity,\nand the recent depression has given them\na chance to catcii up, so that I believe\nthat they are about even now.\n\"The production of cotton seed oil and\nkindred products is limited to about four\nmonths in the year, and I think that industry\nhas been uninterrupted and very\nprofitable. Car building, of course, has\nbeen curtailed because of a lack of orders\nfrom railroads, and there has been\na very general interruption of railroad\ni building and improvements in this section.\nThere is comparatively little going\non at this time, and it is impossible to\npredict when it will be resumed. Certainly,\nit is not reasonable to expect any\nresumption of railroad extension or construction\nor general development in transportation\nor other public utilities until\nconfidence, so terribly scattered by the\nagitation of several years past and the\nrecent panic, shall have been restore^. It\ntakes but a very short time to destroy\nconfidence and to impair credit, but it\ntakes a long time to recover it.\nLumber Mills Shut Down.\n\n\"Many of the lumber mills in this state\nshut down some weeks ago because of\ngeneral stagnation in the market for\ntheir products. This is due to the interruption\nof building, railway construction\nand the suspension of other operations\nwhich call for that kind of material. The\nrailways in the south, as in other parts\nof the country, have been using an enormous\namount of timber and lumber in\ntheir improvements. There has been an\nunprecedented amount of building in Atlanta\nand other cities of the south for the\nItoore tifblob Ko c Q bcrtrhArl pnn\n1 last 1C w jicai a, niiiv.ii nao uuovi\nI siderable portion of the output of our\nj saw-mills, which are located In the south'\nern and southwestern portions of the\nstate, and that furnished a good deal of\ntraffic. They have shipped a great deal\ni of material north also for which there is\nj no longer any demand, but I understand\nthat business is picking up again in the\nbuilding line and will resume normal conditions\nshortly.\n\"The state of Georgia has shared to a\nvery large, extent in the prosperity that\nhas prevailed throughout the country\nduring the last three years, but I have\nnot the figures at hand to even roughly\nestimate our increase in wealth and In\nthe volume of business transactions. But\neverybody knows that both have been\nenormous. The south was nev^- in so\ngood a condition as when the panic occurred\nlast fall. It is impossible to estimate\nhow long the depression will last,\nbut everything looks very encouraging.\nWhen we emerge from it I think Georgia\nwill continue to progress, not rapidly, hut\nsteadily, for we have all the essential\nconditions down here, the materiai resources\nare Inexhaustible, our agricultural\ninterests are a source of wealth\nthat cannot be taken away, and the products\nof this state are of such a character\nthat the world needs them and cannot\nget along without them.\"\n\"Are wages higher than in previous\nyears?\"\nIncrease in Wages.\n\"Yes. They have advanced materially.\nCommon railroad labor now commands\n40 per cent more wages than It did ten\nyears ago and farmers are paying a great\ndeal more for their help than formerly,\nbut I cannot give you the exact figures.\nLocomotive engineers and firemen are also\nreceiving much more than they did ten\nyears ago. The wages of conductors and\ntrainmen have increased, but not in tlie\nsame ratio as those of engineers and iire,\nmen and ordinary labor. Rallroah clerks,\n1 telegraph operators and other employes of\ntransportation lines have enjoyed some\nadvance, but it has not been general or\nuniform. The average Increase in the\npay-rolls of the railway companies has\nbeen considerable and has affected every\nman more or less.\n\"At the same time, passenger rates have\nbeen reduced by legislation from three\ncents a mile to two and a half cents on\nsome of the principal railroads, to two and\na quarter cents on others and to two cents\non still others. There are also continual\nattempts betngr made to reduce freight\nrates by applications to the railroad commission.\nSometimes these demands are\nsuccessful and sometimes not, but the\ngeneral tendency of railway rates, both\nfor passengers and freights, has been\ndownward tor several years, while the\ntendency of wages has been upward.\n\"The money Invested in r.\"v railrdhd\nenterprises In Georgia for many years\npast has nearly all come from outside the\nstate. It is quite certain, however, that\nsome local money has been put into new\nenterprises, but, as a rule, it nas only\nremained Invested In that way until the\nprojectors could sell their interests to railroad\ncompanies already established.\"\n\"What portion of the community in\nGeorgia has enjoyed the greatest degree\nof prosperity?\"\nProsperity of the Farmers.\n\"1 should say that the, farmers have\ndone better than any other distinct class\nof citizens. At least theip prosperity has\nbeen more apparent and tangible. We\nknow what lias happened to them because\nthe amount of their products is a\nmatter of record as well as the price at\nwhich they have been sold. Many of the\nfarmers, according o the best information\n1 can get, have been able to hold\ntheir cotton on the farms and sell it only\nwhen they conld obtain the price that\nsuited them. This is a very significant\nl fact and it illustrates the remarkable\n1 change that has been going on among the\nplantations of Georgia and other states\nin the south. For generations the cotton\nplanters lived ahead of their incomes and\nwere invariably compelled to borrow\nmoney to put in their crops. This situai\ntion rendered them wholly unable to con!\ntrol the marketing of tiheir products. But\nnow very few of them are in debt and\nr many of them are so well fixed thut they\ncan practically dictate their own prices,\nor, at least, they are able to hold on to\ntheir cotton until the price reaches a\npoint that pleases them.\"\ni \"What lias been the actual cause of the\ndecrease in railway earnings?\"\nRailway Earnings Fall Off.\n\"Several causes 'have contributed. The\nfact that the farmers have been able to\nhold bark their cotton from market is\none of them.\" continued Mr. Scott. \"The 3\nmovement of cotton has been very slpw y\nthis x-r>ar while tliev have been waiting t\nfor higher prices. This has reacted upon\nthe movement of bouh fertilizers and iner- J,\nchandise, because if the farmer holds his\ncotton back and does not sell It. he Is 4\nwithout the cash necessary to purchase y\na vast number of articles included in the y\nname of merchandise. V\n\"He curtails his purchases in many V\nthings, not only conducive to the comfort\nof Jiis family, but of everything which\ncan be classed under the head of luxuries. 1\nThen. too. he defers the purchase of fer-\ntilizer for his next planting until llie latest\npossible moment.\n\"There has been a very large decrease\nin the movement of general merchandise\nand still larger in fertilizers. The prep- y\naration of the soil for tne next crop is y\nvery backward this season, due to differ- y\nent causes. One of tiiem is the unwilling- V\nness of tlie farmers to strain their credit y\nwhile they are holding their cotton to J?\npurchase fertilizers which they want to\nput on the ground about the same time\nthey sow their seed. It is quite possible .t,\nthat the planting season will be protracted J,\nthrough the month of May this year In\nGeorgia and that in the meantime there\nwill be a large movement in fertilizers. y\nHope and Confidence. ]jj!\nI find that every one I have talked with V\ndown here agrees with Mr. Scott con-\ncerning present conditions and future .J\nprospects. Everybody is hopeful; every-\nbody is confident, and as long as the\npresent feeling continues, there need be no\nanxiety concerning the financial or in-\ndustrial prosperity of this section. As y\nMr. Scott has said, the farmers have very y\ngenerally escaped from the clutches of the V\nmoney lender. They have not only paic.\noff their mortgages, but are now working\non a cash basis Only a few years ago\nSO per cent of the planters in the south J\ni.... i V\nwere compelled 10 sen or morisaBt; unn.\ncrop before it was planted. The commis- a\nsion houses or the merchants or the A\nmoney lenders would advance the funds A\nto pay for their seed, their implements y\nand their help and even furnish their y\nliving supplies during the meantime, y\ncharging a high rate of interest for such y\nadvances and taking practically every y\ndollar of the proceeds of the cotton that\nwas raised. Very often the crop would\nnot sell for enough to meet these ad- J\nvances and the credit would lap over on\nthe next year's crop or a mortgage placed\nupon the land. That method of management\nkept the south poor, but a succession\nof fat years and fat prices has en- a\nabled#the planters to pay up their debts A\nand to secure their release from the ob- 5\nligations which made them miserable. ?5\nIt is also a significant and gratifying\nfact that the planters of the south are y\ndiversifying their crops. They are rais-\ning a large part of their own supplies. V\nInstead of sending north for their cornmeal\nand bacon they are producing it on\ntheir own farms. They are going in for\nall kinds of crops, particularly fruit, watermelons\narid vegetables of all kinds.\nThe statistics of agricultural development ?J\nin Georgia and other southern states show\nas great a variety of products as those\nof the northern states. While the volume\nof cotton produced has grown larger and ?j\nlarger every year, the corn, wheat, oats, 'j\nbarley, beans, peas and other staples have y\nincreased in the same degree. The num- *t\nber of cattle, sheep, swine, horses and\nmules has grown every year until now\nGeorgia ranks high in the list of pork ,1\nproducers, and is second only to Missouri\nin the number of mules produced. 4\nEffect of Northern Invasion. J\nThis change is due. in a measure, to the\nadvent of northern men. who have\nbrought down no'thern ways and have\ndemonstrated the advantages of diversi-\ntied crops. 0\nIt is also due to a considerable degree E\nto the influence of the Department of\nAgriculture at Washington, to the gov- 11\nernment experimental stations and the e\nestablishment of agricultural schools and V\ncolleges in the south. Thirty, or even b\ntwenty, years ago a southern planter\nwrmlH harp in srnrn u sue\ngestion that he send his sons to school\nto learn how to run a plantation. But q\ntoday there are agricultural schools all\nover the south, and they are filled with\nintelligent, eager young men. learning\nme science 01 i arming, me economy or\nmanagement and the most profitable\nmethods of applying labor. These schools\nhave been of enormous practical value. It\nand have increased the income of the f<\nplantation population to a degree that is\nalmost incredible.\nAnother important reason for this d\nchange in conditions is the division of\nthe large plantations into small farms.\nWhile there are several very large estates tj\nin this part of the country under a single w\nownership and management, the tendency\nis to divide the land and tor the owner to cj\nwork it himself without trusting his in-\nterests to the indifference or dishonesty\nof an overseer. a\nGIFT FROM MRS. SAGE. d.\na\n$250,000 for a Doimitory for Prince- t)\nton Freshmen.\nPRINCETON. N. J.. April 10,-At a\nmeeting of the trustees of Princeton held\nyesterday afternoon a gift of $250,000\nfrom Mrs. Russell Sage was announced.\nThe offer came in a letter in wiiich Mrs. q\nSage said that her plan was to give a\ndormitory to Princeton suitable for freshmen.\nHitherto the first year men have\nhad to seek accommodations in town.\nThe only restricting clause in the offer\nis that Mrs. Sage reserves the right to approve\nthe choice of the architect and the\nplans of the building. The trustees accepted\nthe offer unanimously and voted d\ntheir thanks to Mrs. Sage. t<\nA number of small gifts amounting to P\n$1:50.133 were also announced. P\nThe trustees voted to establish a com- w\ntnons in University Hall, where the freshmen\nnow eat. This move, it Is thought.\nwill do much toward solving the social\nnx/kklom f kn 1 f\\ nror nluccov liooo ticn in V\nvruicni vi mv iv v, v wunuov in\nthe past the sophomores have had to take\ntheir meals at various boarding houses\naround town, where the food was- not a\nalways good and the price always high. F\nAs many upper classmen as possible will\nbe accommodated at the new commons.\nThe trustees decided to place the buildings\nfor the new graduate school on the\ngTounds of Prospect. It 1s understood\nthat the president s house will be moved\nso that the present gardens and lawns\nwill become the Fellows garden. si\nd\nCOOKE NOW ACCUSES BISHOP. t,\nt h\nCharges of Maladministration Fol-\nlow the Day Case. w\nRUTLAND, Vt? April lO.-Rev. George P\nA. Cooke of Brandon, whose recent a\ncharges against Chancellor Day of Syra- t]\ncuse University, alleging that the chan- s<\nceilor had publicly attacked President\nRoosevelt, were not sustained, has pre- jj\nferred chargees of maladministration n\nagainst Bishop Moore of the New York w\nconference, uhere the Day case came\nup for consideration. Mr. Cooke says\ntliat he told Bishop Moore he would at- s\ntack the latter if the bishop used lits G\noffice to shield Day, and he wishes the S(\npublic to know that the light against\nChancellor Day is not ended. p\nIn the charges Mr. Cooke asserts that\nas .presiding officer of the New York s\nconference, which met at New York April\n1, Bishop Moore was guilty of gross be- w\ntrayal of trust, amounting to corrupt\nand partisan administration of his office. 11\nCooke declares that the bishop, without d<\nsanction from the discipline committee, ir\nthrew his charges of defamation of char- w\nacter against Chancellor James R. Day w\nout of the conference, allowing the char- h\nacter of Dr. Day to pass without investi- e<\ngation and without a trial. Cooke says si\nthat the procedure was illegal and revolu- ir\ntionary and calculated to encourage crime it\namong the ministers. n\nn\nSUMMER CONVENTION RATES.\nFare and a Half Agreed to by East- si\nern Roads.\nCHICAGO. April 10.?After several k\nmonths of controversy over the question\nof special rates eastern, railroads yester-\nday practically decided to grant round\ntrip rates of a fare and a half for the\nlarger conventions this summer.\nThis means that the rates already an- i>\nnounced by western roads for the re- t(\npublican national/ convention at Chicago d<\nwill be given from eastern points. A ti\nlarge number of other gatherings in the b\nterritory of the Central i'assehger Associa- si\nR. HARRIS CO., M\nIJ?? (C^TI\nA L\nApppopri;\nAn umsMrpassed di\nmarked at prices that\n[iarsc Bags,\nWe have a host of pretty effects\nin Hand Bags in German\nand sterling silver. All the\nnewest styles are shown.\nWe offer a special for this\nweek in a Fine Ger- /\\jf>\nman Silver Hand\nOthers at $7.o0, $10, $12, up\nto $40.\nCombs.\nA pretty Comb is an essen'\ntial part of the toilet. Our\nstock includes all the newest\nideas.\nWe offer a special in a Solid\nGold Mounted ap an\nComb; for this week j| J\nat\nOthers at $:i. $4. $7>, and up to\n$2o.\nWe Import Ok\nDirect from the cutters in A\ncan offer unequaled values an\nI assortment to choose from.\nand original mountings mad<\nonly.\nWe offor a special for this we\nDiamond Ring?Tiffany setting?1\nstone, for\n\nIR. MAKE]\non. including that of the Grand Arm;\nf the Republic at Toledo, the Nationa\nkiucationsl Association and the Baptls\noung People's Union at Cleveland, an<\nne more important of the fraternal gath\nrings will also have special rates. Las\near practically no concessions were mad<\ny the railroads in the central territory.\nLEAGUE TO BOOH GRAY.\nombine of Prominent Democrats it\nFour Middle States.\nPHILADELPHIA. Pa., April 10.? Fiftj\nell known democrats from Pennsylvania\new Jersey, Delaware and Maryland me\nist night at the Hotel Walton ant\nirmed the George Gray League to worl\n>r the nomination of Judge Gray of Del\nware for President.\nThe Gray League, it was announced, wll\ne made a national movement. An appea\nthe voters of the country setting forti\nle qualifications of the Delaware juris\nill be issued in a few nays, neaaquar\n?rs will be established either in thii\nity or in Washington. John dadwaladei\nf this city presided at the meeting. 1\nA charter for the league was draftee\nnd it was signed by 'Jt?0 persons. Thes*\niclude the most prominent advocates oi\nemocracy in the four states representee\nt the meeting.\nIt was also confidently asserted tha\nlese four states, with the addition ol\n/est Virginia, will vote on the first bal\na at the democratic convention in Den\ner for Judge Gray.\nOPEN SHOP ON GREAT LAKES.\narriers' Association Will Not Recognize\nUnions.\nCLEVELAND. April 10.?The open shor\nn the Great Lakes was promulgated b>\nle Lake Carriers' Association here yes?rday.\nBy unanimous vote the vessel owners\neclared against recognition of the unions\nThe carriers' executive committee is\nirected to grant a fair rate of wages and\nprovide for the comfort of all emloyes,\nin return demanding diligent and\nrompt service. Union men, it was said,\nould be employed, signing individuality\nThe engineers of the Pittsburg Steamhip\nCompany, the United States Stee\norporation's fleet, agreed to sign indlidual\ncontracts and afflix their slgnaires.\nJoseph Blanchett of BufTalo, business\ngent of the marine engineers, visitec\n'resident Livingstone of the carriers, bul\n.Ivingstone told him there was nothing\ndiscuss.\ns\nWrote Wife He Would End Life.\nNEW YORK, April 10? Capt. W. D\n'urner of Nashville, Tenn., a well knowr\noutherner, disappeared In this city Fri\nay last and the police have been aske<\n3. look for him. Capt. Turner wrote i\ntter to his wife the day he droppet\nrom sight saying he intended t<\nonimit suicide. Detective Conrov. whi\nas detailed yesterday to search for Tur\ner, says he can find no trace of him. H<\nas scanned the records of the morgu<\nnd hospitals, but no person who answeri\nhe description of Turner has killed him\nelf or been taken to the hospital sinc<\nipril 3. Chief of Police Henry Curran o\n.'ashville, who asked the New York po\nice to look for Turner, writes that th<\nlissiivg man left Nashville April\n,-ithout notifying his wife or friendi\n,'liere he intended to go. A few dayi\niter Mrs. Turner received a letter fron\ner husband, dated April 3. and posted a\ntation P. New York, which is at Bowlinj\nIreen, declaring he intended to kill him\nelf.\n'our Shot During Election Hurrah.\nperial Dispatch to The Star.\nKENOSHA. Wis., April 10.?Four men\nrere shot last night during the celebraon\nover the victory of M. J. Scholey,\nmiocratic mayor-elect. Supporters of the\nlayor-elect were marching along Milaukee\navenue when a shotgun loaded\n1th buckshot was discharged by Gerard\nBuclimann, who had been elected\n[instable on the democratic ticket. The\ntot struck the cement sidewalk and flew\ni all directions. Otto Wellman was shot\nl eighteen places and Frank Engel, Erest\nPipendorf and Peter Peler received\numerous wounds.\nAgainst Unfair Trade Methods.\npecial Cablegram to The Star.\nHONGKONG. April 10.?The Hongong\nChamber of Commerce has sent ciruiar?\nto the chambers of commerce at\nondon, Manchester. Liverpool, Shanghai,\nientsin and elsewhere, suggesting that\niplomatic action be taken against the\nroposal of the Japanese Cotton Spinners'\nssociation to insert lottery tickets in\nales of cotton yarn as an inducement\nbuyers, thus aiding the Japanese to the\netriment of the Indian trade. British\nmis are willing to face fair competition,\nut protest against the artificial means of\nEmulating trade.\nmanufacturing Jewelers, 7th\nnating M??\nate for Eas\nispflay of beautiful things\ncannot be duplicated in thi\nBelt Buckles.\nW e are showing a superb\nstock of pretty Belt Buckles to\nmatch the new Easter gowns.\nWe offer a special this week\nin a very Hand- ?1 E^/TV\nsome Buckle 05tJ)\nOthers at $2. $4. and $7..\"A\nLavalliers.\nAn extremely pretty assortment\nof artistic designs in gold\nand enamel, set with pearls or\njewels. Many new ideas.\nWe offer a special in an Exceedingly\nDainty a\nI aralller nf new rl#>- VX/II (1 il\nsign; for........\nOthers at $5,' $7.TiO, $tO and up\nto $500.\ni\nCut Glass.\nOur stock of Cut GJass is\ntruly magnificent,. and the\nprices are by .far .the lowest\nyou can find aj\\y\\vJiere.\nWe offer special a Beautiful\nCut Glass Dish, with p\nhandle. Result K J!\nvalue. For\n\nnmonds Our St*\nmsterdam, and Is absolutely i\nd an unequaled for reliability.\nSee the new watch trade 01\nin our factory make prices t\nJ of other deale\nA typical\nek in a a* mm week is a La<\nlawless SiSfl D 14\"k K?,d cast\nElgin moveme\nis ccvi